# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: synaptic-transmission
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] At a chemical synapse, one neuron releases neurotransmitter molecules into a small space (the synaptic cleft) that is adjacent to the postsynaptic cell (e.g., another neuron).
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The neurotransmitter molecules are contained within small sacs called synaptic vesicles, and are released into the synaptic cleft by exocytosis.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] These molecules then bind to neurotransmitter receptors on the postsynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Finally, to terminate its action, the neurotransmitter is cleared from the cleft through one of several mechanisms, including enzymatic degradation or re-uptake, by specific transporters, either into the presynaptic cell or to neuroglia.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The adult human brain is estimated to contain from 1014 to 5 × 1014 (100–500 trillion) synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Every cubic millimeter of cerebral cortex contains roughly a billion (short scale, i.e.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The word "synapse" was introduced by Sir Charles Scott Sherrington in 1897.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Chemical synapses are not the only type of biological synapse: electrical and immunological synapses also exist.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Without a qualifier, however, "synapse" commonly refers to chemical synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Synapses are functional connections between neurons, or between neurons and other types of cells.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] A typical neuron gives rise to several thousand synapses, although there are some types that make far fewer.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Most synapses connect axons to dendrites, but there are also other types of connections, including axon-to-cell-body, axon-to-axon, and dendrite-to-dendrite.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Synapses are generally too small to be recognizable using a light microscope except as points where the membranes of two cells appear to touch, but their cellular elements can be visualized clearly using an electron microscope.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Chemical synapses pass information directionally from a presynaptic cell to a postsynaptic cell and are therefore asymmetric in structure and function.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Some synaptic vesicles are docked at the presynaptic plasma membrane at regions called active zones.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Immediately opposite is a region of the postsynaptic cell containing neurotransmitter receptors; for synapses between two neurons the postsynaptic region may be found on the dendrites or cell body.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Immediately behind the postsynaptic membrane is an elaborate complex of interlinked proteins called the postsynaptic density (PSD).
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Proteins in the PSD are involved in anchoring and trafficking neurotransmitter receptors and modulating the activity of these receptors.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The receptors and PSDs are often found in specialized protrusions from the main dendritic shaft called dendritic spines.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Synapses may be described as symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] When examined under an electron microscope, asymmetric synapses are characterized by rounded vesicles in the presynaptic cell, and a prominent postsynaptic density.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Asymmetric synapses are typically excitatory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Symmetric synapses in contrast have flattened or elongated vesicles, and do not contain a prominent postsynaptic density.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Symmetric synapses are typically inhibitory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The **synaptic cleft**—also called **synaptic gap**—is a gap between the pre- and postsynaptic cells that is about 20 nm (0.02 μ) wide.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The small volume of the cleft allows neurotransmitter concentration to be raised and lowered rapidly.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] An autapse is a chemical (or electrical) synapse formed when the axon of one neuron synapses with its own dendrites.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Some authors consider signal transmission at a chemical synapse as a special case of paracrine signaling., while others treat it a separate signaling mechanism.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Here is a summary of the sequence of events that take place in synaptic transmission from a presynaptic neuron to a postsynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Each step is explained in more detail below.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Note that with the exception of the final step, the entire process may run only a few hundred microseconds, in the fastest synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The electrical depolarization of the membrane at the synapse causes channels to open that are permeable to calcium ions.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Calcium ions flow through the presynaptic membrane, rapidly increasing the calcium concentration in the interior.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The high calcium concentration activates a set of calcium-sensitive proteins attached to vesicles that contain a neurotransmitter chemical.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] These proteins change shape, causing the membranes of some "docked" vesicles to fuse with the membrane of the presynaptic cell, thereby opening the vesicles and dumping their neurotransmitter contents into the synaptic cleft, the narrow space between the membranes of the pre- and postsynaptic cells.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The neurotransmitter diffuses within the cleft.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Some of it escapes, but some of it binds to chemical receptor molecules located on the membrane of the postsynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The binding of neurotransmitter causes the receptor molecule to be *activated* in some way.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Several types of activation are possible, as described in more detail below.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] In any case, this is the key step by which the synaptic process affects the behavior of the postsynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Due to thermal vibration, the motion of atoms, vibrating about their equilibrium positions in a crystalline solid, neurotransmitter molecules eventually break loose from the receptors and drift away.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The neurotransmitter is either reabsorbed by the presynaptic cell, and then repackaged for future release, or else it is broken down metabolically.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The release of a neurotransmitter is triggered by the arrival of a nerve impulse (or action potential) and occurs through an unusually rapid process of cellular secretion (exocytosis).
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Within the presynaptic nerve terminal, vesicles containing neurotransmitter are localized near the synaptic membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The arriving action potential produces an influx of calcium ions through voltage-dependent, calcium-selective ion channels at the down stroke of the action potential (tail current).
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Calcium ions then bind to synaptotagmin proteins found within the membranes of the synaptic vesicles, allowing the vesicles to fuse with the presynaptic membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The fusion of a vesicle is a stochastic process, leading to frequent failure of synaptic transmission at the very small synapses that are typical for the central nervous system.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Large chemical synapses (e.g. the neuromuscular junction), on the other hand, have a synaptic release probability, in effect, of 1.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Vesicle fusion is driven by the action of a set of proteins in the presynaptic terminal known as SNAREs.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] As a whole, the protein complex or structure that mediates the docking and fusion of presynaptic vesicles is called the active zone.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The membrane added by the fusion process is later retrieved by endocytosis and recycled for the formation of fresh neurotransmitter-filled vesicles.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] An exception to the general trend of neurotransmitter release by vesicular fusion is found in the type II receptor cells of mammalian taste buds.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Here the neurotransmitter ATP is released directly from the cytoplasm into the synaptic cleft via voltage gated channels.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Receptors on the opposite side of the synaptic gap bind neurotransmitter molecules.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Receptors can respond in either of two general ways.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] First, the receptors may directly open ligand-gated ion channels in the postsynaptic cell membrane, causing ions to enter or exit the cell and changing the local transmembrane potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The resulting change in voltage is called a postsynaptic potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] In general, the result is *excitatory* in the case of depolarizing currents, and *inhibitory* in the case of hyperpolarizing currents.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Whether a synapse is excitatory or inhibitory depends on what type(s) of ion channel conduct the postsynaptic current(s), which in turn is a function of the type of receptors and neurotransmitter employed at the synapse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The second way a receptor can affect membrane potential is by modulating the production of chemical messengers inside the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] These second messengers can then amplify the inhibitory or excitatory response to neurotransmitters.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] After a neurotransmitter molecule binds to a receptor molecule, it must be removed to allow for the postsynaptic membrane to continue to relay subsequent EPSPs and/or IPSPs.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The strength of a synapse has been defined by Bernard Katz as the product of (presynaptic) release probability *pr*, quantal size *q* (the postsynaptic response to the release of a single neurotransmitter vesicle, a 'quantum'), and *n*, the number of release sites.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] "Unitary connection" usually refers to an unknown number of individual synapses connecting a presynaptic neuron to a postsynaptic neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The amplitude of postsynaptic potentials (PSPs) can be as low as 0.4 mV to as high as 20 mV.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The amplitude of a PSP can be modulated by neuromodulators or can change as a result of previous activity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Changes in the synaptic strength can be short-term, lasting seconds to minutes, or long-term (long-term potentiation, or LTP), lasting hours.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Learning and memory are believed to result from long-term changes in synaptic strength, via a mechanism known as synaptic plasticity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Desensitization of the postsynaptic receptors is a decrease in response to the same neurotransmitter stimulus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] It means that the strength of a synapse may in effect diminish as a train of action potentials arrive in rapid succession – a phenomenon that gives rise to the so-called frequency dependence of synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The nervous system exploits this property for computational purposes, and can tune its synapses through such means as phosphorylation of the proteins involved.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Synaptic transmission can be changed by previous activity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] These changes are called synaptic plasticity and may result in either a decrease in the efficacy of the synapse, called depression, or an increase in efficacy, called potentiation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] These changes can either be long-term or short-term.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Forms of short-term plasticity include synaptic fatigue or depression and synaptic augmentation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Forms of long-term plasticity include long-term depression and long-term potentiation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Synaptic plasticity can be either homosynaptic (occurring at a single synapse) or heterosynaptic (occurring at multiple synapses).
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Homosynaptic plasticity (or also homotropic modulation) is a change in the synaptic strength that results from the history of activity at a particular synapse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] This can result from changes in presynaptic calcium as well as feedback onto presynaptic receptors, i.e. a form of autocrine signaling.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Homosynaptic plasticity can affect the number and replenishment rate of vesicles or it can affect the relationship between calcium and vesicle release.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Homosynaptic plasticity can also be postsynaptic in nature.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] It can result in either an increase or decrease in synaptic strength.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] One example is neurons of the sympathetic nervous system (SNS), which release noradrenaline, which, besides affecting postsynaptic receptors, also affects presynaptic α2-adrenergic receptors, inhibiting further release of noradrenaline.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] This effect is utilized with clonidine to perform inhibitory effects on the SNS.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Heterosynaptic plasticity (or also heterotropic modulation) is a change in synaptic strength that results from the activity of other neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Again, the plasticity can alter the number of vesicles or their replenishment rate or the relationship between calcium and vesicle release.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Additionally, it could directly affect calcium influx.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Heterosynaptic plasticity can also be postsynaptic in nature, affecting receptor sensitivity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] One example is again neurons of the sympathetic nervous system, which release noradrenaline, which, in addition, generates an inhibitory effect on presynaptic terminals of neurons of the parasympathetic nervous system.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] In general, if an excitatory synapse is strong enough, an action potential in the presynaptic neuron will trigger an action potential in the postsynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] In many cases the excitatory postsynaptic potential (EPSP) will not reach the threshold for eliciting an action potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] When action potentials from multiple presynaptic neurons fire simultaneously, or if a single presynaptic neuron fires at a high enough frequency, the EPSPs can overlap and summate.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] If enough EPSPs overlap, the summated EPSP can reach the threshold for initiating an action potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] This process is known as summation, and can serve as a high pass filter for neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] If an IPSP overlaps with an EPSP, the IPSP can in many cases prevent the neuron from firing an action potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] In this way, the output of a neuron may depend on the input of many different neurons, each of which may have a different degree of influence, depending on the strength and type of synapse with that neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] John Carew Eccles performed some of the important early experiments on synaptic integration, for which he received the Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine in 1963.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] When a neurotransmitter is released at a synapse, it reaches its highest concentration inside the narrow space of the synaptic cleft, but some of it is certain to diffuse away before being reabsorbed or broken down.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] If it diffuses away, it has the potential to activate receptors that are located either at other synapses or on the membrane away from any synapse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] The extrasynaptic activity of a neurotransmitter is known as *volume transmission*.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] It is well established that such effects occur to some degree, but their functional importance has long been a matter of controversy.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Recent work indicates that volume transmission may be the predominant mode of interaction for some special types of neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] In the mammalian cerebral cortex, a class of neurons called neurogliaform cells can inhibit other nearby cortical neurons by releasing the neurotransmitter GABA into the extracellular space.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] GABA released from neurogliaform cells into the extracellular space also acts on surrounding astrocytes, assigning a role for volume transmission in the control of ionic and neurotransmitter homeostasis.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Approximately 78% of neurogliaform cell boutons do not form classical synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] This may be the first definitive example of neurons communicating chemically where classical synapses are not present.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] An electrical synapse is an electrically conductive link between two abutting neurons that is formed at a narrow gap between the pre- and postsynaptic cells, known as a gap junction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] At gap junctions, cells approach within about 3.5 nm of each other, rather than the 20 to 40 nm distance that separates cells at chemical synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] As opposed to chemical synapses, the postsynaptic potential in electrical synapses is not caused by the opening of ion channels by chemical transmitters, but rather by direct electrical coupling between both neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Electrical synapses are faster than chemical synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Electrical synapses are found throughout the nervous system, including in the retina, the reticular nucleus of the thalamus, the neocortex, and in the hippocampus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] While chemical synapses are found between both excitatory and inhibitory neurons, electrical synapses are most commonly found between smaller local inhibitory neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Electrical synapses can exist between two axons, two dendrites, or between an axon and a dendrite.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] In some fish and amphibians, electrical synapses can be found within the same terminal of a chemical synapse, as in Mauthner cells.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] One of the most important features of chemical synapses is that they are the site of action for the majority of psychoactive drugs.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Synapses are affected by drugs, such as curare, strychnine, cocaine, morphine, alcohol, LSD, risperidone, and countless others.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] These drugs have different effects on synaptic function, and often are restricted to synapses that use a specific neurotransmitter.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] For example, curare is a poison that stops acetylcholine from depolarizing the postsynaptic membrane, causing paralysis.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Strychnine blocks the inhibitory effects of the neurotransmitter glycine, which causes the body to pick up and react to weaker and previously ignored stimuli, resulting in uncontrollable muscle spasms.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Morphine acts on synapses that use endorphin neurotransmitters, and alcohol increases the inhibitory effects of the neurotransmitter GABA.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] LSD interferes with synapses that use the neurotransmitter serotonin.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Risperidone is a blocker of various receptors including several dopamine and serotonin receptors, and it can bind with high affinity to some types of serotonin receptors.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Cocaine blocks reuptake of dopamine and therefore increases its effects.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] During the 1950s, Bernard Katz and Paul Fatt observed spontaneous miniature synaptic currents at the frog neuromuscular junction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] Based on these observations, they developed the 'quantal hypothesis' that is the basis for our current understanding of neurotransmitter release as exocytosis and for which Katz received the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1970.
[src:synaptic-transmission/chemical-synapse] In the late 1960s, Ricardo Miledi and Katz advanced the hypothesis that depolarization-induced influx of calcium ions triggers exocytosis.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] An **electrical synapse** is a synapse in which electrical current flows directly from one cell to another via a gap junction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] It is one of the two major classes of synapses, the other being the chemical synapse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] At a gap junction, the two neurons are separated by a very narrow gap of about 2–4 nm of each other, a distance much smaller than the 20- to 40-nanometer distance that separates cells at a chemical synapse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Electrical synapses co-exist with chemical synapses in the nervous system of many animals, from nematodes to arthropods to vertebrates, including mammals.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Most synapses in the brain are chemical, but electrical synapses are an important minority with a distinct purpose.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Compared to chemical synapses, electrical synapses conduct nerve impulses faster and provide continuous-time bidirectional coupling via linked cytoplasm.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] As such, the notion of signal directionality across these synapses is not always defined.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] They are known to produce synchronization of network activity in the brain and can create chaotic network level dynamics.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] In situations where a signal direction can be defined, they lack gain (unlike chemical synapses)—the signal in the postsynaptic neuron is the same or smaller than that of the originating neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] The fundamental bases for perceiving electrical synapses comes down to the connexons that are located in the gap junction between two neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Electrical synapses are often found in neural systems that require the fastest possible response, such as defensive reflexes.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] An important characteristic of electrical synapses is that they are mostly bidirectional, allowing impulse transmission in either direction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Each gap junction (sometimes called a *nexus*) contains numerous gap junction channels that cross the plasma membranes of both cells.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] With a lumen diameter of about 1.2 to 2.0 nm, the pore of a gap junction channel is wide enough to allow ions and even medium-size molecules like signaling molecules to flow from one cell to the next, thereby connecting the two cells' cytoplasm.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Thus when the membrane potential of one cell changes, ions may move through from one cell to the next, carrying positive charge with them and depolarizing the postsynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Gap junction channels are composed of two hemichannels called connexons in vertebrates, one contributed by each cell at the synapse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Connexons are formed by six 7.5 nm long, four-pass membrane-spanning protein subunits called connexins, which may be identical or slightly different from one another.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] An autapse is an electrical (or chemical) synapse formed when the axon of one neuron synapses with its own dendrites.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] They are found in many regions in animal and human body.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] The simplicity of electrical synapses results in synapses that are fast, but more importantly the bidirectional coupling can produce very complex behaviors at the network level.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] The relative speed of electrical synapses also allows for many neurons to fire synchronously.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Because of the speed of transmission, electrical synapses are found in escape mechanisms and other processes that require quick responses, such as the response to danger of the sea hare *Aplysia*, which quickly releases large quantities of ink to obscure enemies' vision.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Normally, current carried by ions could travel in either direction through this type of synapse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] However, sometimes the junctions are rectifying synapses, containing voltage-gated ion channels that open in response to depolarization of an axon's plasma membrane, and prevent current from traveling in one of the two directions.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Some channels may also close in response to increased calcium (Ca2+ ) or hydrogen (H+ ) ion concentration, so as not to spread damage from one cell to another.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] There is also evidence of synaptic plasticity where the electrical connection established can either be strengthened or weakened as a result of activity, or during changes in the intracellular concentration of magnesium.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Other examples of functional gap junctions detected *in vivo* are in the striatum, cerebellum, and suprachiasmatic nucleus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] The model of a reticular network of directly interconnected cells was one of the early hypotheses for the organization of the nervous system at the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] This reticular hypothesis was considered to conflict directly with the now predominant *neuron doctrine*, a model in which isolated, individual neurons signal to each other chemically across synaptic gaps.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Golgi delivered his Nobel lecture first, in part detailing evidence for a reticular model of the nervous system.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Ramón y Cajal then took the podium and refuted Golgi's conclusions in his lecture.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Modern understanding of the coexistence of chemical and electrical synapses, however, suggests that both models are physiologically significant; it could be said that the Nobel committee acted with great foresight in awarding the Prize jointly.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Thus, the discovery of electrical communication was surprising.
[src:synaptic-transmission/electrical-synapse] Electrical synapses were first demonstrated between escape-related giant neurons in crayfish in the late 1950s, and were later found in vertebrates.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] In neuroscience, an **excitatory postsynaptic potential** (**EPSP**) is a postsynaptic potential that makes the postsynaptic neuron more likely to fire an action potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] This temporary depolarization of postsynaptic membrane potential, caused by the flow of positively charged ions into the postsynaptic cell, is a result of opening ligand-gated ion channels.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] These are the opposite of inhibitory postsynaptic potentials (IPSPs), which usually result from the flow of *negative* ions into the cell or positive ions *out* of the cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] EPSPs can also result from a decrease in outgoing positive charges, while IPSPs are sometimes caused by an increase in positive charge outflow.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] The flow of ions that causes an EPSP is an **excitatory postsynaptic current** (**EPSC**).
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] EPSPs, like IPSPs, are graded (i.e. they have an additive effect).
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] When multiple EPSPs occur on a single patch of postsynaptic membrane, their combined effect is the sum of the individual EPSPs.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] Larger EPSPs result in greater membrane depolarization and thus increase the likelihood that the postsynaptic cell reaches the threshold for firing an action potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] EPSPs in living cells are caused chemically.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] When an active presynaptic cell releases neurotransmitters into the synapse, some of them bind to receptors on the postsynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] Many of these receptors contain an ion channel capable of passing positively charged ions either into or out of the cell (such receptors are called ionotropic receptors).
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] At excitatory synapses, the ion channel typically allows sodium into the cell, generating an excitatory postsynaptic current.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] This depolarizing current causes an increase in membrane potential, the EPSP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] The neurotransmitter most often associated with EPSPs is the amino acid glutamate, and is the main excitatory neurotransmitter in the central nervous system of vertebrates.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] Its ubiquity at excitatory synapses has led to it being called *the* excitatory neurotransmitter.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] In some invertebrates, glutamate is the main excitatory transmitter at the neuromuscular junction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] In the neuromuscular junction of vertebrates, EPP (end-plate potentials) are mediated by the neurotransmitter acetylcholine, which (along with glutamate) is one of the primary transmitters in the central nervous system of invertebrates.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] At the same time, GABA is the most common neurotransmitter associated with IPSPs in the brain.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] However, classifying neurotransmitters as such is technically incorrect, as there are several other synaptic factors that help determine a neurotransmitter's excitatory or inhibitory effects.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] The release of neurotransmitter vesicles from the presynaptic cell is probabilistic.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] In fact, even without stimulation of the presynaptic cell, a single vesicle will occasionally be released into the synapse, generating miniature EPSPs (mEPSPs).
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] Bernard Katz pioneered the study of these mEPSPs at the neuromuscular junction (often called miniature end-plate potentials) in 1951, revealing the quantal nature of synaptic transmission.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] *Quantal size* can then be defined as the synaptic response to the release of neurotransmitter from a single vesicle, while *quantal content* is the number of effective vesicles released in response to a nerve impulse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] *Quantal analysis* refers to the methods used to deduce, for a particular synapse, how many quanta of transmitter are released and what the average effect of each quantum is on the target cell, measured in terms of amount of ions flowing (charge) or change in the membrane potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] EPSPs are usually recorded using intracellular electrodes.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] The extracellular signal from a single neuron is extremely small and thus next to impossible to record in the human brain.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] However, in some areas of the brain, such as the hippocampus, neurons are arranged in such a way that they all receive synaptic inputs in the same area.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] Because these neurons are in the same orientation, the extracellular signals from synaptic excitation don't cancel out, but rather add up to give a signal that can easily be recorded with a field electrode.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] This extracellular signal recorded from a population of neurons is the field potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] In studies of hippocampal long-term potentiation (LTP), figures are often given showing the field EPSP (fEPSP) in stratum radiatum of CA1 in response to Schaffer collateral stimulation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] This is the signal seen by an extracellular electrode placed in the layer of apical dendrites of CA1 pyramidal neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] The Schaffer collaterals make excitatory synapses onto these dendrites, and so when they are activated, there is a current sink in stratum radiatum: the field EPSP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] The voltage deflection recorded during a field EPSP is negative-going, while an intracellularly recorded EPSP is positive-going.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] This difference is due to the relative flow of ions (primarily the sodium ion) into the cell, which, in the case of the field EPSP is away from the electrode, while for an intracellular EPSPs it is towards the electrode.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] After a field EPSP, the extracellular electrode may record another change in electrical potential named the population spike which corresponds to the population of cells firing action potentials (spiking).
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] In other regions than CA1 of the hippocampus, the field EPSP may be far more complex and harder to interpret as the source and sinks are far less defined.
[src:synaptic-transmission/excitatory-postsynaptic-potential] In regions such as the striatum, neurotransmitters such as dopamine, acetylcholine, GABA and others may also be released and further complicate the interpretation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In neuroscience, **long-term potentiation** (**LTP**) is a persistent strengthening of synapses based on recent patterns of activity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] These are patterns of synaptic activity that produce a long-lasting increase in signal transmission between two neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The opposite of LTP is long-term depression, which produces a long-lasting decrease in synaptic strength.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] It is one of several phenomena underlying synaptic plasticity, the ability of chemical synapses to change their strength.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] As memories are thought to be encoded by modification of synaptic strength, LTP is widely considered one of the major cellular mechanisms that underlies learning and memory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] LTP was discovered in the rabbit hippocampus by Terje Lømo in 1966 and has remained a popular subject of research since.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Many modern LTP studies seek to better understand its basic biology, while others aim to draw a causal link between LTP and behavioral learning.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Still, others try to develop methods, pharmacologic or otherwise, of enhancing LTP to improve learning and memory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] LTP is also a subject of clinical research, for example, in the areas of Alzheimer's disease and addiction medicine.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] At the end of the 19th century, scientists generally recognized that the number of neurons in the adult brain (roughly 100 billion) did not increase significantly with age, giving neurobiologists good reason to believe that memories were generally not the result of new neuron production.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] With this realization came the need to explain how memories could form in the absence of new neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The Spanish neuroanatomist Santiago Ramón y Cajal was among the first to suggest a mechanism of learning that did not require the formation of new neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In his 1894 Croonian Lecture, he proposed that memories might instead be formed by strengthening the connections between existing neurons to improve the effectiveness of their communication.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Eric Kandel (1964) and associates were some of the first researchers to discover long-term potentiation during their work with sea slug Aplysia.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] They attempted to apply behavioral conditioning to different cells in the slug's neural network.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Their results showed synaptic strength changes and researchers suggested that this may be due to a basic form of learning occurring within the slug.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] These skills would not come until the later half of the 20th century, at about the same time as the discovery of long-term potentiation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] LTP was first observed by Terje Lømo in 1966 in the Oslo, Norway, laboratory of Per Andersen.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] There, Lømo conducted a series of neurophysiological experiments on anesthetized rabbits to explore the role of the hippocampus in short-term memory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Lømo's experiments focused on connections, or synapses, from the perforant pathway to the dentate gyrus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] These experiments were carried out by stimulating presynaptic fibers of the perforant pathway and recording responses from a collection of postsynaptic cells of the dentate gyrus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] As expected, a single pulse of electrical stimulation to fibers of the perforant pathway caused excitatory postsynaptic potentials (EPSPs) in cells of the dentate gyrus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] What Lømo unexpectedly observed was that the postsynaptic cells' response to these single-pulse stimuli could be enhanced for a long period of time if he first delivered a high-frequency train of stimuli to the presynaptic fibers.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] When such a train of stimuli was applied, subsequent single-pulse stimuli elicited stronger, prolonged EPSPs in the postsynaptic cell population.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] This phenomenon, whereby a high-frequency stimulus could produce a long-lived enhancement in the postsynaptic cells' response to subsequent single-pulse stimuli, was initially called "long-lasting potentiation".
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Timothy Bliss, who joined the Andersen laboratory in 1968, collaborated with Lømo and in 1973 the two published the first characterization of long-lasting potentiation in the rabbit hippocampus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Bliss and Tony Gardner-Medwin published a similar report of long-lasting potentiation in the awake animal which appeared in the same issue as the Bliss and Lømo report.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In 1975, Douglas and Goddard proposed "long-term potentiation" as a new name for the phenomenon of long-lasting potentiation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Andersen suggested that the authors chose "long-term potentiation" perhaps because of its easily pronounced acronym, "LTP".
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The physical and biological mechanism of LTP is still not understood, but some successful models have been developed.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Mathematical models such as BCM Theory, which depends also on intracellular calcium in relation to NMDA receptor voltage gates, have been developed since the 1980s and modify the traditional *a priori* Hebbian learning model with both biological and experimental justification.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Still, others have proposed re-arranging or synchronizing the relationship between receptor regulation, LTP, and synaptic strength.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Since its original discovery in the rabbit hippocampus, LTP has been observed in a variety of other neural structures, including the cerebral cortex, cerebellum, amygdala, and many others.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Robert Malenka, a prominent LTP researcher, has suggested that LTP may even occur at all excitatory synapses in the mammalian brain.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Different areas of the brain exhibit different forms of LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The specific type of LTP exhibited between neurons depends on a number of factors.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] One such factor is the age of the organism when LTP is observed.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] For example, the molecular mechanisms of LTP in the immature hippocampus differ from those mechanisms that underlie LTP of the adult hippocampus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The signalling pathways used by a particular cell also contribute to the specific type of LTP present.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] For example, some types of hippocampal LTP depend on the NMDA receptor, others may depend upon the metabotropic glutamate receptor (mGluR), while still others depend upon another molecule altogether.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The variety of signaling pathways that contribute to LTP and the wide distribution of these various pathways in the brain are reasons that the type of LTP exhibited between neurons depends only in part upon the anatomic location in which LTP is observed.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] For example, LTP in the Schaffer collateral pathway of the hippocampus is NMDA receptor-dependent - this was proved by the application of AP5, an antagonist to the NMDA receptor, which prevented LTP in this pathway.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Conversely, LTP in the mossy fiber pathway is NMDA receptor-independent, even though both pathways are in the hippocampus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The pre- and postsynaptic activity required to induce LTP are other criteria by which LTP is classified.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Broadly, this allows classification of LTP into Hebbian, non-Hebbian, and anti-Hebbian mechanisms.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Borrowing its name from Hebb's postulate, summarized by the maxim that "cells that fire together wire together," **Hebbian LTP** requires simultaneous pre- and postsynaptic depolarization for its induction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] **Non-Hebbian LTP** is a type of LTP that does not require such simultaneous depolarization of pre- and postsynaptic cells; an example of this occurs in the mossy fiber hippocampal pathway.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] A special case of non-Hebbian LTP, **anti-Hebbian LTP** explicitly requires simultaneous presynaptic depolarization and relative postsynaptic hyperpolarization for its induction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Owing to its predictable organization and readily inducible LTP, the CA1 hippocampus has become the prototypical site of mammalian LTP study.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In particular, NMDA receptor-dependent LTP in the adult CA1 hippocampus is the most widely studied type of LTP, and is therefore, the focus of this article.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] NMDA receptor-dependent LTP exhibits several properties, including input specificity, associativity, cooperativity, and persistence.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Long-term potentiation is only propagated to those synapses according to the rules of associativity and cooperativity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] However, the input specificity of LTP may be incomplete at short distances.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] refers to the observation that when weak stimulation of a single pathway is insufficient for the induction of LTP, simultaneous strong stimulation of another pathway will induce LTP at both pathways.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] When one pathway into a synapse is stimulated weakly, it produces insufficient postsynaptic depolarization to induce LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In contrast, when weak stimuli are applied to many pathways that converge on a single patch of postsynaptic membrane, the individual postsynaptic depolarizations generated may collectively depolarize the postsynaptic cell enough to induce LTP cooperatively.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Synaptic tagging, discussed later, may be a common mechanism underlying associativity and cooperativity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] argues that any difference between associativity and cooperativity is strictly semantic.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] While induction entails the *transient* activation of CaMKII and PKC, maintenance of E-LTP (early-form LTP) is characterized by their *persistent* activation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] During this stage PKMzeta (PKMζ) which does not have dependence on calcium, become autonomously active.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Consequently, they are able to carry out the phosphorylation events that underlie E-LTP expression.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Phosphorylation is a chemical reaction in which a small phosphate group is added to another molecule to change that molecule's activity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Autonomously active CaMKII and PKC use phosphorylation to carry out the two major mechanisms underlying the expression of E-LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] First, and most importantly, they phosphorylate existing AMPA receptors to increase their activity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Second, they mediate or modulate the insertion of additional AMPA receptors into the postsynaptic membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Importantly, the delivery of AMPA receptors to the synapse during E-LTP is independent of protein synthesis.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] This is achieved by having a nonsynaptic pool of AMPA receptors adjacent to the postsynaptic membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] When the appropriate LTP-inducing stimulus arrives, nonsynaptic AMPA receptors are rapidly trafficked into the postsynaptic membrane under the influence of protein kinases.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] As mentioned previously, AMPA receptors are the brain's most abundant glutamate receptors and mediate the majority of its excitatory activity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] By increasing the efficiency and number of AMPA receptors at the synapse, future excitatory stimuli generate larger postsynaptic responses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] While the above model of E-LTP describes entirely postsynaptic mechanisms for induction, maintenance, and expression, an additional component of expression may occur presynaptically.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] One hypothesis of this presynaptic facilitation is that persistent CaMKII activity in the postsynaptic cell during E-LTP may lead to the synthesis of a "retrograde messenger", discussed later.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] According to this hypothesis, the newly synthesized messenger travels across the synaptic cleft from the postsynaptic to the presynaptic cell, leading to a chain of events that facilitate the presynaptic response to subsequent stimuli.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Such events may include an increase in neurotransmitter vesicle number, probability of vesicle release, or both.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In addition to the retrograde messenger underlying presynaptic expression in early LTP, the retrograde messenger may also play a role in the expression of late LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Late LTP (L-LTP) is the natural extension of E-LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Unlike E-LTP, which is independent of protein synthesis, L-LTP requires gene transcription and protein synthesis in the postsynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Two phases of L-LTP exist: the first depends upon protein synthesis, while the second depends upon both gene transcription and protein synthesis.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] These phases are occasionally called LTP2 and LTP3, respectively, with E-LTP referred to as LTP1 under this nomenclature.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Late LTP is induced by changes in gene expression and protein synthesis brought about by the persistent activation of protein kinases activated during E-LTP, such as MAPK.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In fact, MAPK—specifically the extracellular signal-regulated kinase (ERK) subfamily of MAPKs—may be the molecular link between E-LTP and L-LTP, since many signaling cascades involved in E-LTP, including CaMKII and PKC, can converge on ERK.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Recent research has shown that the induction of L-LTP can depend on coincident molecular events, namely PKA activation and calcium influx, that converge on CRTC1 (TORC1), a potent transcriptional coactivator for cAMP response element binding protein (CREB).
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] This requirement for a molecular coincidence accounts perfectly for the associative nature of LTP, and, presumably, for that of learning.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Upon activation, ERK may phosphorylate a number of cytoplasmic and nuclear molecules that ultimately result in the protein synthesis and morphological changes observed in L-LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] These cytoplasmic and nuclear molecules may include transcription factors such as CREB.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] ERK-mediated changes in transcription factor activity may trigger the synthesis of proteins that underlie the maintenance of L-LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] One such molecule may be protein kinase Mζ (PKMζ), a persistently active kinase whose synthesis increases following LTP induction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] PKMζ is an atypical isoform of PKC that lacks a regulatory subunit and thus remains constitutively active.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Unlike other kinases that mediate LTP, PKMζ is active not just in the first 30 minutes following LTP induction; rather, PKMζ becomes a requirement for LTP maintenance only during the late phase of LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] PKMζ thus appears important for the persistence of memory and would be expected to be important in the maintenance of long-term memory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Indeed, administration of a PKMζ inhibitor into the hippocampus of the rat results in retrograde amnesia with intact short-term memory; PKMζ does not play a role in the establishment of short-term memory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] PKMζ has recently been shown to underlie L-LTP maintenance by directing the trafficking and reorganization of proteins in the synaptic scaffolding that underlie the expression of L-LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Even more recently, transgenic mice lacking PKMζ demonstrate normal LTP, questioning the necessity of PKMζ.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In return it was argued that the related molecule PKC-ι/λ (PKC-ι and PKC-λ isoforms) acted as a compensatory mechanism.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] It has been also shown that PKMζ works together with KIBRA in anchoring its activity so that when a protein degrades and needs to be replaced, the other remains in place, therefore more crucial than each molecule individually is the interaction between them in the maintenance of L-LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The long-term stabilization of synaptic changes is also determined by a parallel increase of pre- and postsynaptic structures such as axonal bouton, dendritic spine and postsynaptic density.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] On the molecular level, an increase of the postsynaptic scaffolding proteins PSD-95 and Homer1c has been shown to correlate with the stabilization of synaptic enlargement.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The identities of only a few proteins synthesized during L-LTP are known.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Regardless of their identities, it is thought that they contribute to the increase in dendritic spine number, surface area, and postsynaptic sensitivity to neurotransmitter associated with L-LTP expression.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The latter may be brought about in part by the enhanced synthesis of AMPA receptors during L-LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Late LTP is also associated with the presynaptic synthesis of synaptotagmin and an increase in synaptic vesicle number, suggesting that L-LTP induces protein synthesis not only in postsynaptic cells, but in presynaptic cells as well.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] As mentioned previously, for postsynaptic LTP induction to result in presynaptic protein synthesis, there must be communication from the postsynaptic to the presynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] This may occur via the synthesis of a retrograde messenger, discussed later.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Even in studies restricted to postsynaptic events, investigators have not determined the location of the protein synthesis that underlies L-LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Specifically, it is unclear whether protein synthesis takes place in the postsynaptic cell body or in its dendrites.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Despite having observed ribosomes (the major components of the protein synthesis machinery) in dendrites as early as the 1960s, prevailing wisdom was that the cell body was the predominant site of protein synthesis in neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] This reasoning was not seriously challenged until the 1980s, when investigators reported observing protein synthesis in dendrites whose connection to their cell body had been severed.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] More recently, investigators have demonstrated that this type of local protein synthesis is necessary for some types of LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] One reason for the popularity of the local protein synthesis hypothesis is that it provides a possible mechanism for the specificity associated with LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Specifically, if indeed local protein synthesis underlies L-LTP, only dendritic spines receiving LTP-inducing stimuli will undergo LTP; the potentiation will not be propagated to adjacent synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] By contrast, global protein synthesis that occurs in the cell body requires that proteins be shipped out to every area of the cell, including synapses that have not received LTP-inducing stimuli.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Whereas local protein synthesis provides a mechanism for specificity, global protein synthesis would seem to directly compromise it.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] However, as discussed later, the synaptic tagging hypothesis successfully reconciles global protein synthesis, synapse specificity, and associativity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Retrograde signaling is a hypothesis that attempts to explain that, while LTP is induced and expressed postsynaptically, some evidence suggests that it is expressed presynaptically as well.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The hypothesis gets its name because normal synaptic transmission is directional and proceeds from the presynaptic to the postsynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] For induction to occur postsynaptically and be partially expressed presynaptically, a message must travel from the postsynaptic cell to the presynaptic cell in a *retrograde* (reverse) direction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Once there, the message presumably initiates a cascade of events that leads to a presynaptic component of expression, such as the increased probability of neurotransmitter vesicle release.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Retrograde signaling is currently a contentious subject as some investigators do not believe the presynaptic cell contributes at all to the expression of LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Even among proponents of the hypothesis there is controversy over the identity of the messenger.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Early thoughts focused on nitric oxide, while most recent evidence points to cell adhesion proteins.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Before the local protein synthesis hypothesis gained significant support, there was general agreement that the protein synthesis underlying L-LTP occurred in the cell body.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Further, there was thought that the products of this synthesis were shipped cell-wide in a nonspecific manner.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] It thus became necessary to explain how protein synthesis could occur in the cell body without compromising LTP's input specificity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The synaptic tagging hypothesis attempts to solve the cell's difficult problem of synthesizing proteins in the cell body but ensuring they only reach synapses that have received LTP-inducing stimuli.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The synaptic tagging hypothesis proposes that a "synaptic tag" is synthesized at synapses that have received LTP-inducing stimuli, and that this synaptic tag may serve to capture plasticity-related proteins shipped cell-wide from the cell body.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Studies of LTP in the marine snail *Aplysia californica* have implicated synaptic tagging as a mechanism for the input-specificity of LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] There is some evidence that given two widely separated synapses, an LTP-inducing stimulus at one synapse drives several signaling cascades (described previously) that initiates gene expression in the cell nucleus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] At the same synapse (but not the unstimulated synapse), local protein synthesis creates a short-lived (less than three hours) synaptic tag.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The products of gene expression are shipped globally throughout the cell, but are only captured by synapses that express the synaptic tag.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Thus only the synapse receiving LTP-inducing stimuli is potentiated, demonstrating LTP's input specificity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The synaptic tag hypothesis may also account for LTP's associativity and cooperativity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Associativity (*see Properties*) is observed when one synapse is excited with LTP-inducing stimulation while a separate synapse is only weakly stimulated.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Whereas one might expect only the strongly stimulated synapse to undergo LTP (since weak stimulation alone is insufficient to induce LTP at either synapse), *both* synapses will in fact undergo LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] While weak stimuli are unable to induce protein synthesis in the cell body, they may prompt the synthesis of a synaptic tag.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Simultaneous strong stimulation of a separate pathway, capable of inducing cell body protein synthesis, then may prompt the production of plasticity-related proteins, which are shipped cell-wide.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] With both synapses expressing the synaptic tag, both would capture the protein products resulting in the expression of LTP in both the strongly stimulated and weakly stimulated pathways.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Cooperativity is observed when two synapses are activated by weak stimuli incapable of inducing LTP when stimulated individually.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] But upon simultaneous weak stimulation, both synapses undergo LTP in a cooperative fashion.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Synaptic tagging does not explain how multiple weak stimuli can result in a collective stimulus sufficient to induce LTP (this is explained by the postsynaptic summation of EPSPs described previously).
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Rather, synaptic tagging explains the ability of weakly stimulated synapses, none of which are capable of independently generating LTP, to receive the products of protein synthesis initiated collectively.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] As before, this may be accomplished through the synthesis of a local synaptic tag following weak synaptic stimulation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] As described previously, the molecules that underlie LTP can be classified as mediators or modulators.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] A mediator of LTP is a molecule, such as the NMDA receptor or calcium, whose presence and activity is necessary for generating LTP under nearly all conditions.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] By contrast, a modulator is a molecule that can alter LTP but is not essential for its generation or expression.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In addition to the signaling pathways described above, hippocampal LTP may be altered by a variety of modulators.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] For example, the steroid hormone estradiol may enhance LTP by driving CREB phosphorylation and subsequent dendritic spine growth.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Additionally, β-adrenergic receptor agonists such as norepinephrine may alter the protein synthesis-dependent late phase of LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Nitric oxide synthase activity may also result in the subsequent activation of guanylyl cyclase and PKG.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Similarly, activation of dopamine receptors may enhance LTP through the cAMP/PKA signaling pathway.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] While the long-term potentiation of synapses in cell culture seems to provide an elegant substrate for learning and memory, the contribution of LTP to behavioral learning — that is, learning at the level of the whole organism — cannot simply be extrapolated from *in vitro* studies.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] For this reason, considerable effort has been dedicated to establishing whether LTP is a requirement for learning and memory in living animals.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Because of this, LTP also plays a crucial role in fear processing.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In 1986, Richard Morris provided some of the first evidence that LTP was indeed required for the formation of memories *in vivo*.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] He tested the spatial memory of rats by pharmacologically modifying their hippocampus, a brain structure whose role in spatial learning is well established.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Rats were trained on the Morris water maze, a spatial memory task in which rats swim in a pool of murky water until they locate the platform hidden beneath its surface.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] During this exercise, normal rats are expected to associate the location of the hidden platform with salient cues placed at specific positions around the circumference of the maze.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] After training, one group of rats had their hippocampi bathed in the NMDA receptor blocker APV, while the other group served as the control.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Both groups were then subjected to the water maze spatial memory task.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Rats in the control group were able to locate the platform and escape from the pool, while the performance of APV-treated rats was significantly impaired.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Moreover, when slices of the hippocampus were taken from both groups, LTP was easily induced in controls, but could not be induced in the brains of APV-treated rats.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] This provided early evidence that the NMDA receptor — and by extension, LTP — was required for at least some types of learning and memory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Similarly, Susumu Tonegawa demonstrated in 1996 that the CA1 area of the hippocampus is crucial to the formation of spatial memories in living mice.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] So-called *place cells* located in this region become active only when the rat is in a particular location — called a *place field* — in the environment.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Since these place fields are distributed throughout the environment, one interpretation is that groups of place cells form maps in the hippocampus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The accuracy of these maps determines how well a rat learns about its environment and thus how well it can navigate it.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Tonegawa found that by impairing the NMDA receptor, specifically by genetically removing the NR1 subunit in the CA1 region, the place fields generated were substantially less specific than those of controls.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] That is, mice produced faulty spatial maps when their NMDA receptors were impaired.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] As expected, these mice performed very poorly on spatial tasks compared to controls, further supporting the role of LTP in spatial learning.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Enhanced NMDA receptor activity in the hippocampus has also been shown to produce enhanced LTP and an overall improvement in spatial learning.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In 1999, Tang *et al*. produced a line of mice with enhanced NMDA receptor function by overexpressing the NR2B subunit in the hippocampus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The resulting smart mice, nicknamed "Doogie mice" after the fictional prodigious doctor Doogie Howser, had larger LTP and excelled at spatial learning tasks, reinforcing LTP's importance in the formation of hippocampus-dependent memories.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In 2006, Jonathan Whitlock and colleagues reported on a series of experiments that provided perhaps the strongest evidence of LTP's role in behavioral memory, arguing that to conclude that LTP underlies behavioral learning, the two processes must both mimic and occlude one another.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Employing an inhibitory avoidance learning paradigm, researchers trained rats in a two-chambered apparatus with light and dark chambers, the latter being fitted with a device that delivered a foot shock to the rat upon entry.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] An analysis of CA1 hippocampal synapses revealed that inhibitory avoidance training induced *in vivo* AMPA receptor phosphorylation of the same type as that seen in LTP *in vitro*; that is, inhibitory avoidance training mimicked LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In addition, synapses potentiated during training could not be further potentiated by experimental manipulations that would have otherwise induced LTP; that is, inhibitory avoidance training occluded LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The role of LTP in disease is less clear than its role in basic mechanisms of synaptic plasticity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] However, alterations in LTP may contribute to a number of neurological diseases, including depression, Parkinson's disease, epilepsy, and neuropathic pain.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Impaired LTP may also have a role in Alzheimer's disease and drug addiction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] LTP has received much attention among those who study Alzheimer's disease (AD), a neurodegenerative disease that causes marked cognitive decline and dementia.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Much of this deterioration occurs in association with degenerative changes in the hippocampus and other medial temporal lobe structures.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Because of the hippocampus' well established role in LTP, some have suggested that the cognitive decline seen in individuals with AD may result from impaired LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] In a 2003 review of the literature, Rowan *et al.* proposed one model for how LTP might be affected in AD.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] AD appears to result, at least in part, from misprocessing of amyloid precursor protein (APP).
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] The result of this abnormal processing is the accumulation of fragments of this protein, called amyloid β (Aβ).
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Aβ exists in both soluble and fibrillar forms.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Misprocessing of APP results in the accumulation of soluble Aβ that, according to Rowan's hypothesis, impairs hippocampal LTP and may lead to the cognitive decline seen early in AD.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] AD may also impair LTP through mechanisms distinct from Aβ.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] For example, one study demonstrated that the enzyme PKMζ accumulates in neurofibrillary tangles, which are a pathologic marker of AD.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] PKMζ is an enzyme with critical importance in the maintenance of late LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Research in the field of addiction medicine has also recently turned its focus to LTP, owing to the hypothesis that drug addiction represents a powerful form of learning and memory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Addiction is a complex neurobehavioral phenomenon involving various parts of the brain, such as the ventral tegmental area (VTA) and nucleus accumbens (NAc).
[src:synaptic-transmission/long-term-potentiation] Studies have demonstrated that VTA and NAc synapses are capable of undergoing LTP and that this LTP may be responsible for the behaviors that characterize addiction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] In response to a threshold action potential or graded electrical potential, a neurotransmitter is released at the presynaptic terminal.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The released neurotransmitter may then move across the synaptic cleft to be bind to receptors in the membrane of the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Binding of neurotransmitters may influence the postsynaptic neuron in either an inhibitory or excitatory way.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The binding of neurotransmitters to receptors in the postsynaptic neuron can trigger either short term changes, such as changes in the membrane potential called postsynaptic potentials, or longer term changes by the activation of signaling cascades.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Neurons form complex biological neural networks through which nerve impulses (action potentials) travel.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Neurons do not touch each other (except in the case of an electrical synapse through a gap junction); instead, neurons interact at close contact points called synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] A neuron transports its information by way of an action potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] When the nerve impulse arrives at the synapse, it may cause the release of neurotransmitters, which influence another (postsynaptic) neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The postsynaptic neuron may receive inputs from many additional neurons, both excitatory and inhibitory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The excitatory and inhibitory influences are summed, and if the net effect is inhibitory, the neuron will be less likely to "fire" (i.e., generate an action potential), and if the net effect is excitatory, the neuron will be more likely to fire.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] How likely a neuron is to fire depends on how far its membrane potential is from the threshold potential, the voltage at which an action potential is triggered because enough voltage-dependent sodium channels are activated so that the net inward sodium current exceeds all outward currents.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Excitatory inputs bring a neuron closer to threshold, while inhibitory inputs bring the neuron farther from threshold.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] An action potential is an "all-or-none" event; neurons whose membranes have not reached threshold will not fire, while those that do must fire.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Once the action potential is initiated (traditionally at the axon hillock), it will propagate along the axon, leading to release of neurotransmitters at the synaptic bouton to pass along information to yet another adjacent neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Storage of the neurotransmitter in vesicles in the axon terminal.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Before synaptic transmission there is a high concentration of Ca ions outside the axon terminals.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Nerve impulse (depolarization) reaches the axon terminal.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Calcium diffuses into the axon terminal causing vesicles adjacent to axon terminals to fuse with the plasma membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Fusing results in release of the neurotransmitter into the synaptic cleft.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] After its release, the transmitter diffuses across the synpatic cleft and binds to neurotransmitter gated ion channels on the membrane of the postsynaptic dendrite (next nerve).
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Binding of the neurotransmitter stimulates adjacent Na voltage gates channels on the postsynaptic membrane to open and activates a receptor in the postsynaptic membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Na diffuses though Na voltage gated channels into postsynaptic dendrite triggering depolarization of the downstream neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The neurotransmitter is either destroyed enzymatically, or taken back into the terminal from which it came, where it can be reused, or degraded and removed.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Neurotransmitters are spontaneously packed in vesicles and released in individual quanta-packets independently of presynaptic action potentials.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] This slow release is detectable and produces micro-inhibitory or micro-excitatory effects on the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] An action potential briefly amplifies this process.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Neurotransmitters containing vesicles cluster around active sites, and after they have been released may be recycled by one of three proposed mechanisms.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The first proposed mechanism involves partial opening and then re-closing of the vesicle.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The second two involve the full fusion of the vesicle with the membrane, followed by recycling, or recycling into the endosome.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Vesicular fusion is driven largely by the concentration of calcium in micro domains located near calcium channels, allowing for only microseconds of neurotransmitter release, while returning to normal calcium concentration takes a couple of hundred of microseconds.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The vesicle exocytosis is thought to be driven by a protein complex called SNARE, that is the target for botulinum toxins.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Once released, a neurotransmitter enters the synapse and encounters receptors.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Neurotransmitter receptors can either be ionotropic or g protein coupled.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Ionotropic receptors allow for ions to pass through when agonized by a ligand.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The main model involves a receptor composed of multiple subunits that allow for coordination of ion preference.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] G protein coupled receptors, also called metabotropic receptors, when bound to by a ligand undergo conformational changes yielding in intracellular response.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Termination of neurotransmitter activity is usually done by a transporter, however enzymatic deactivation is also plausible.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Each neuron connects with numerous other neurons, receiving numerous impulses from them.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] **Summation** is the adding together of these impulses at the axon hillock.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] If the neuron only gets excitatory impulses, it will generate an action potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] If instead the neuron gets as many inhibitory as excitatory impulses, the inhibition cancels out the excitation and the nerve impulse will stop there.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Action potential generation is proportionate to the probability and pattern of neurotransmitter release, and to postsynaptic receptor sensitization.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Neurotransmission implies both a convergence and a divergence of information.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] First one neuron is influenced by many others, resulting in a convergence of input.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] When the neuron fires, the signal is sent to many other neurons, resulting in a divergence of output.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Many other neurons are influenced by this neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] At the nerve terminal, neurotransmitters are present within 35–50 nm membrane-encased vesicles called synaptic vesicles.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] To release neurotransmitters, the synaptic vesicles transiently dock and fuse at the base of specialized 10–15 nm cup-shaped lipoprotein structures at the presynaptic membrane called porosomes.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The neuronal porosome proteome has been solved, providing the molecular architecture and the complete composition of the machinery.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Recent studies in a myriad of systems have shown that most, if not all, neurons release several different chemical messengers.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Cotransmission allows for more complex effects at postsynaptic receptors, and thus allows for more complex communication to occur between neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] In modern neuroscience, neurons are often classified by their cotransmitter.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] For example, striatal "GABAergic neurons" utilize opioid peptides or substance P as their primary cotransmitter.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Some neurons can release at least two neurotransmitters at the same time, the other being a cotransmitter, in order to provide the stabilizing negative feedback required for meaningful encoding, in the absence of inhibitory interneurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Noradrenaline and ATP are sympathetic co-transmitters.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] It is found that the endocannabinoid anadamide and the cannabinoid WIN 55,212-2 can modify the overall response to sympathetic nerve stimulation, and indicate that prejunctional CB1 receptors mediate the sympatho-inhibitory action.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Thus cannabinoids can inhibit both the noradrenergic and purinergic components of sympathetic neurotransmission.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] One unusual pair of co-transmitters is GABA and glutamate which are released from the same axon terminals of neurons originating from the ventral tegmental area (VTA), internal globus pallidus, and supramammillary nucleus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] The former two project to the habenula whereas the projections from the supramammillary nucleus are known to target the dentate gyrus of the hippocampus.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] Neurotransmission is genetically associated with other characteristics or features.
[src:synaptic-transmission/neurotransmission] For example, enrichment analyses of different signaling pathways led to the discovery of a genetic association with intracranial volume.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In the nervous system, a **synapse** is a structure that allows a neuron to exchange (receive or send) signals with another cell in its immediate vicinity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Synapses can be classified as either chemical or electrical, depending on the mechanism of signal transmission between neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In the case of electrical synapses, neurons are coupled bidirectionally with each other through gap junctions and have a connected cytoplasmic milieu.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] These types of synapses are known to produce synchronous network activity in the brain, but can also result in complicated, chaotic network level dynamics.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Therefore, signal directionality cannot always be defined across electrical synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Synapses are essential for the transmission of neuronal impulses from one neuron to the next, playing a key role in enabling rapid and direct communication by creating circuits.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In addition, a synapse serves as a junction where both the transmission and processing of information occur, making it a vital means of communication between neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] At the synapse, the plasma membrane of the signal-passing neuron (the *presynaptic* neuron) comes into close apposition with the membrane of the target (*postsynaptic*) cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Both the presynaptic and postsynaptic sites contain extensive arrays of molecular machinery that link the two membranes together and carry out the signaling process.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In many synapses, the presynaptic part is located on the terminals of axons and the postsynaptic part is located on a dendrite or soma.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Astrocytes also exchange information with neurons, responding to synaptic activity and, in turn, regulating neurotransmission.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Synapses (at least chemical synapses) are stabilized in position by synaptic adhesion molecules (SAMs)[1] projecting from both the pre- and post-synaptic neuron and sticking together where they overlap; SAMs may also assist in the generation and functioning of synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Moreover, SAMs coordinate the formation of synapses, with various types working together to achieve the remarkable specificity of synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In essence, SAMs function in both excitatory and inhibitory synapses, likely serving as the mediator for signal transmission.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] This suggests that the source (*presynaptic* cell) of the signal is always a neuron, while the target (*postsynaptic* cell) may be a neuron or a non-neuronal cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] However, synapses where a non-neuronal cell is the source of the signal exist in many sensory systems, such as auditory, vestibular or tactile systems, where specialized epithelial receptor cells transmit signals to neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Santiago Ramón y Cajal proposed that neurons are not continuous throughout the body, yet still communicate with each other, an idea known as the neuron doctrine.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The word "synapse" was introduced in 1897 by the English neurophysiologist Charles Sherrington in Michael Foster's *Textbook of Physiology*.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Sherrington struggled to find a good term that emphasized a union between two *separate* elements, and the actual term "synapse" was suggested by the English classical scholar Arthur Woollgar Verrall, a friend of Foster.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The word was derived from the Greek *synapsis* (σύναψις), meaning "conjunction", which in turn derives from *synaptein* (συνάπτειν), from *syn* (σύν) "together" and *haptein* (ἅπτειν) "to fasten".
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] An electron microscope, which became available only in the 1950s, turned out to be necessary to show the finer structure of the synapse with its separate, parallel pre- and postsynaptic membranes and processes, and the cleft between the two.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Chemical and electrical synapses are two ways of synaptic transmission.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The formation of neural circuits in nervous systems appears to heavily depend on the crucial interactions between chemical and electrical synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Thus these interactions govern the generation of synaptic transmission.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Synaptic communication is distinct from an ephaptic coupling, in which communication between neurons occurs via indirect electric fields.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] An autapse is a chemical or electrical synapse that forms when the axon of one neuron synapses onto dendrites of the same neuron.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Inhibitory synapse: Diminishes the probability of depolarization in postsynaptic neurons and the initiation of an action potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] An influx of Na+ driven by excitatory neurotransmitters opens cation channels, depolarizing the postsynaptic membrane toward the action potential threshold.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In contrast, inhibitory neurotransmitters cause the postsynaptic membrane to become less depolarized by opening either Cl− or K+ channels, reducing firing.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Depending on their release location, the receptors they bind to, and the ionic circumstances they encounter, various transmitters can be either excitatory or inhibitory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] For instance, acetylcholine can either excite or inhibit depending on the type of receptors it binds to.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] For example, glutamate serves as an excitatory neurotransmitter, in contrast to GABA, which acts as an inhibitory neurotransmitter.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Additionally, dopamine is a neurotransmitter that exerts dual effects, displaying both excitatory and inhibitory impacts through binding to distinct receptors.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The membrane potential prevents Cl− from entering the cell, even when its concentration is much higher outside than inside.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The reversal potential for Cl− in many neurons is quite negative, nearly equal to the resting potential.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Opening Cl− channels tends to buffer the membrane potential, but this effect is countered when the membrane starts to depolarize, allowing more negatively charged Cl− ions to enter the cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Consequently, it becomes more difficult to depolarize the membrane and excite the cell when Cl− channels are open.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Similar effects result from the opening of K+ channels.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The significance of inhibitory neurotransmitters is evident from the effects of toxins that impede their activity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] For instance, strychnine binds to glycine receptors, blocking the action of glycine and leading to muscle spasms, convulsions, and death.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Synapses can be classified by the type of cellular structures serving as the pre- and post-synaptic components.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The vast majority of synapses in the mammalian nervous system are classical axo-dendritic synapses (axon synapsing upon a dendrite), however, a variety of other arrangements exist.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] These include but are not limited to axo-axonic, dendro-dendritic, axo-secretory, axo-ciliary, somato-dendritic, dendro-somatic, and somato-somatic synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In fact, the axon can synapse onto a dendrite, onto a cell body, or onto another axon or axon terminal, as well as into the bloodstream or diffusely into the adjacent nervous tissue.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Neurotransmitters are tiny signal molecules stored in membrane-enclosed synaptic vesicles and released via exocytosis.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Indeed, a change in electrical potential in the presynaptic cell triggers the release of these molecules.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] By attaching to transmitter-gated ion channels, the neurotransmitter causes an electrical alteration in the postsynaptic cell and rapidly diffuses across the synaptic cleft.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Once released, the neurotransmitter is swiftly eliminated, either by being absorbed by the nerve terminal that produced it, taken up by nearby glial cells, or broken down by specific enzymes in the synaptic cleft.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Numerous Na+-dependent neurotransmitter carrier proteins recycle the neurotransmitters and enable the cells to maintain rapid rates of release.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] At chemical synapses, transmitter-gated ion channels play a vital role in rapidly converting extracellular chemical impulses into electrical signals.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] These channels are located in the postsynaptic cell's plasma membrane at the synapse region, and they temporarily open in response to neurotransmitter molecule binding, causing a momentary alteration in the membrane's permeability.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Additionally, transmitter-gated channels are comparatively less sensitive to the membrane potential than voltage-gated channels, which is why they are unable to generate self-amplifying excitement on their own.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] However, they result in graded variations in membrane potential due to local permeability, influenced by the amount and duration of neurotransmitter released at the synapse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Recently, mechanical tension, a phenomenon never thought relevant to synapse function has been found to be required for those on hippocampal neurons to fire.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Neurotransmitters bind to ionotropic receptors on postsynaptic neurons, either causing their opening or closing.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The variations in the quantities of neurotransmitters released from the presynaptic neuron may play a role in regulating the effectiveness of synaptic transmission.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In fact, the concentration of cytoplasmic calcium is involved in regulating the release of neurotransmitters from presynaptic neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Loading the neurotransmitters into secretory vesicles.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Controlling the release of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Binding of neurotransmitters to postsynaptic receptors.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Ceasing the activity of the released neurotransmitters.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The function of neurons depends upon cell polarity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The distinctive structure of nerve cells allows action potentials to travel directionally (from dendrites to cell body down the axon), and for these signals to then be received and carried on by post-synaptic neurons or received by effector cells.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Nerve cells have long been used as models for cellular polarization, and of particular interest are the mechanisms underlying the polarized localization of synaptic molecules.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] PIP2 signaling regulated by IMPase plays an integral role in synaptic polarity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Phosphoinositides (PIP, PIP2, and PIP3) are molecules that have been shown to affect neuronal polarity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] A gene (*ttx-7*) was identified in *Caenorhabditis elegans* that encodes *myo*-inositol monophosphatase (IMPase), an enzyme that produces inositol by dephosphorylating inositol phosphate.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Organisms with mutant *ttx-7* genes demonstrated behavioral and localization defects, which were rescued by expression of IMPase.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] This led to the conclusion that IMPase is required for the correct localization of synaptic protein components.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The *egl-8* gene encodes a homolog of phospholipase Cβ (PLCβ), an enzyme that cleaves PIP2.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] When *ttx-7* mutants also had a mutant *egl-8* gene, the defects caused by the faulty *ttx-7* gene were largely reversed.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] These results suggest that PIP2 signaling establishes polarized localization of synaptic components in living neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Modulation of neurotransmitter release by G-protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs) is a prominent presynaptic mechanism for regulation of synaptic transmission.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The activation of GPCRs located at the presynaptic terminal, can decrease the probability of neurotransmitter release.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] This presynaptic depression involves activation of Gi/o-type G-proteins that mediate different inhibitory mechanisms, including inhibition of voltage-gated calcium channels, activation of potassium channels, and direct inhibition of the vesicle fusion process.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Drugs have long been considered crucial targets for transmitter-gated ion channels.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The majority of medications utilized to treat schizophrenia, anxiety, depression, and sleeplessness work at chemical synapses, and many of these pharmaceuticals function by binding to transmitter-gated channels.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] For instance, some drugs like barbiturates and tranquilizers bind to GABA receptors and enhance the inhibitory effect of GABA neurotransmitter.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Thus, reduced concentration of GABA enables the opening of Cl− channels.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Furthermore, psychoactive drugs could potentially target many other synaptic signalling machinery components.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In fact, numerous neurotransmitters are released by Na+-driven carriers and are subsequently removed from the synaptic cleft.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] By inhibiting such carriers, synaptic transmission is strengthened as the action of the transmitter is prolonged.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] For example, Prozac is an antidepressant medication that works by preventing the absorption of serotonin neurotransmitter.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Also, other antidepressants operate by inhibiting the reabsorption of both serotonin and norepinephrine.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In nerve terminals, synaptic vesicles are produced quickly to compensate for their rapid depletion during neurotransmitter release.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Their biogenesis involves segregating synaptic vesicle membrane proteins from other cellular proteins and packaging those distinct proteins into vesicles of appropriate size.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Besides, it entails the endocytosis of synaptic vesicle membrane proteins from the plasma membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] It is widely accepted that the synapse plays a key role in the formation of memory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The stability of long-term memory can persist for many years; nevertheless, synapses, the neurological basis of memory, are very dynamic.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The formation of synaptic connections significantly depends on activity-dependent synaptic plasticity observed in various synaptic pathways.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Indeed, the connection between memory formation and alterations in synaptic efficacy enables the reinforcement of neuronal interactions between neurons.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] As neurotransmitters activate receptors across the synaptic cleft, the connection between the two neurons is strengthened when both neurons are active at the same time, as a result of the receptor's signaling mechanisms.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The strength of two connected neural pathways is thought to result in the storage of information, resulting in memory.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] This process of synaptic strengthening is known as long-term potentiation (LTP).
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] By altering the release of neurotransmitters, the plasticity of synapses can be controlled in the presynaptic cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The postsynaptic cell can be regulated by altering the function and number of its receptors.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Changes in postsynaptic signaling are most commonly associated with a N-methyl-d-aspartic acid receptor (NMDAR)-dependent LTP and long-term depression (LTD) due to the influx of calcium into the post-synaptic cell, which are the most analyzed forms of plasticity at excitatory synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Moreover, Ca2+/calmodulin (CaM)-dependent protein kinase II (CaMKII) is best recognized for its roles in the brain, particularly in the neocortex and hippocampal regions because it serves as a ubiquitous mediator of cellular Ca2+ signals.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] CaMKII is abundant in the nervous system, mainly concentrated in the synapses in the nerve cells.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Indeed, CaMKII has been definitively identified as a key regulator of cognitive processes, such as learning, and neural plasticity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] While Ca2+/CaM binding stimulates CaMKII activity, Ca2+-independent autonomous CaMKII activity can also be produced by a number of other processes.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] CaMKII becomes active by autophosphorylating itself upon Ca2+/calmodulin binding.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] CaMKII is still active and phosphorylates itself even after Ca2+ is cleaved; as a result, the brain stores long-term memories using this mechanism.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Nevertheless, when the CaMKII enzyme is dephosphorylated by a phosphatase enzyme, it becomes inactive, and memories are lost.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Hence, CaMKII plays a vital role in both the induction and maintenance of LTP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Synapses function as ensembles within particular brain networks to control the amount of neuronal activity, which is essential for memory, learning, and behavior.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Consequently, synaptic disruptions might have negative effects.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In fact, alterations in cell-intrinsic molecular systems or modifications to environmental biochemical processes can lead to synaptic dysfunction.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] The synapse is the primary unit of information transfer in the nervous system, and correct synaptic contact creation during development is essential for normal brain function.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] In addition, several mutations have been connected to neurodevelopmental disorders, and that compromised function at different synapse locations is a hallmark of neurodegenerative diseases.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Synaptic defects are causally associated with early appearing neurological diseases, including autism spectrum disorders (ASD), schizophrenia (SCZ), and bipolar disorder (BP).
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] On the other hand, in late-onset degenerative pathologies, such as Alzheimer's (AD), Parkinson's (PD), and Huntington's (HD) diseases, synaptopathy is thought to be the inevitable end-result of an ongoing pathophysiological cascade.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] These diseases are identified by a gradual loss in cognitive and behavioral function and a steady loss of brain tissue.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Moreover, these deteriorations have been mostly linked to the gradual build-up of protein aggregates in neurons, the composition of which may vary based on the pathology; all have the same deleterious effects on neuronal integrity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synapse] Nevertheless, due to limited access to human tissue at late stages and a lack of thorough assessment of the essential components of human diseases in the available experimental animal models, it has been difficult to fully grasp the origin and role of synaptic dysfunction in neurological disorders.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] In a neuron, **synaptic vesicles** (or **neurotransmitter vesicles**) store various neurotransmitters that are released at the synapse.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The release is regulated by a voltage-dependent calcium channel.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Vesicles are essential for propagating nerve impulses between neurons and are constantly recreated by the cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The area in the axon that holds groups of vesicles is an axon terminal or "terminal bouton".
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Up to 130 vesicles can be released per bouton over a ten-minute period of stimulation at 0.2 Hz.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] In the visual cortex of the human brain, synaptic vesicles have an average diameter of 39.5 nanometers (nm) with a standard deviation of 5.1 nm.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Synaptic vesicles are relatively simple because only a limited number of proteins fit into a sphere of 40 nm diameter.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Purified vesicles have a protein:phospholipid ratio of 1:3 with a lipid composition of 40% phosphatidylcholine, 32% phosphatidylethanolamine, 12% phosphatidylserine, 5% phosphatidylinositol, and 10% cholesterol.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Synaptic vesicles contain two classes of obligatory components: transport proteins involved in neurotransmitter uptake, and trafficking proteins that participate in synaptic vesicle exocytosis, endocytosis, and recycling.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The stoichiometry for the movement of different neurotransmitters into a vesicle is given in the following table.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Recently, it has been discovered that synaptic vesicles also contain small RNA molecules, including transfer RNA fragments, Y RNA fragments and mirRNAs.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This discovery is believed to have broad impact on studying chemical synapses.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The tetanus toxin damages vesicle-associated membrane proteins (VAMP), a type of v-SNARE, while botulinum toxins damage t-SNARES and v-SNARES and thus inhibit synaptic transmission.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] A spider toxin called alpha-Latrotoxin binds to neurexins, damaging vesicles and causing massive release of neurotransmitters.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Vesicles in the nerve terminal are grouped into three pools: the readily releasable pool, the recycling pool, and the reserve pool.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] These pools are distinguished by their function and position in the nerve terminal.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The readily releasable pool are docked to the cell membrane, making these the first group of vesicles to be released on stimulation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The readily releasable pool is small and is quickly exhausted.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The recycling pool is proximate to the cell membrane, and tend to be cycled at moderate stimulation, so that the rate of vesicle release is the same as, or lower than, the rate of vesicle formation.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This pool is larger than the readily releasable pool, but it takes longer to become mobilised.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The reserve pool contains vesicles that are not released under normal conditions.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This reserve pool can be quite large (~50%) in neurons grown on a glass substrate, but is very small or absent at mature synapses in intact brain tissue.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Synaptic vesicle components in the presynaptic neuron are initially trafficked to the synapse using members of the kinesin motor family.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] In *C. elegans* the major motor for synaptic vesicles is UNC-104.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] There is also evidence that other proteins such as UNC-16/Sunday Driver regulate the use of motors for transport of synaptic vesicles.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Once at the synapse, synaptic vesicles are loaded with a neurotransmitter.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Loading of transmitter is an active process requiring a neurotransmitter transporter and a proton pump ATPase that provides an electrochemical gradient.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] These transporters are selective for different classes of transmitters.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Characterization of unc-17 and unc-47, which encode the vesicular acetylcholine transporter and vesicular GABA transporter have been described to date.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The loaded synaptic vesicles must dock near release sites, however docking is a step of the cycle that we know little about.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Many proteins on synaptic vesicles and at release sites have been identified, however none of the identified protein interactions between the vesicle proteins and release site proteins can account for the docking phase of the cycle.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Mutants in rab-3 and munc-18 alter vesicle docking or vesicle organization at release sites, but they do not completely disrupt docking.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] SNARE proteins, now also appear to be involved in the docking step of the cycle.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] After the synaptic vesicles initially dock, they must be primed before they can begin fusion.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Priming prepares the synaptic vesicle so that they are able to fuse rapidly in response to a calcium influx.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This priming step is thought to involve the formation of partially assembled SNARE complexes.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The proteins Munc13, RIM, and RIM-BP participate in this event.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Munc13 is thought to stimulate the change of the t-SNARE syntaxin from a closed conformation to an open conformation, which stimulates the assembly of v-SNARE /t-SNARE complexes.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] RIM also appears to regulate priming, but is not essential for the step.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Primed vesicles fuse very quickly with the cell membrane in response to calcium elevations in the cytoplasm.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This releases the stored neurotransmitter into the synaptic cleft.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The fusion event is thought to be mediated directly by the SNAREs and driven by the energy provided from SNARE assembly.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The calcium-sensing trigger for this event is the calcium-binding synaptic vesicle protein synaptotagmin.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The ability of SNAREs to mediate fusion in a calcium-dependent manner recently has been reconstituted in vitro.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Consistent with SNAREs being essential for the fusion process, v-SNARE and t-SNARE mutants of *C. elegans* are lethal.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Similarly, mutants in *Drosophila* and knockouts in mice indicate that these SNARES play a critical role in synaptic exocytosis.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This accounts for the re-uptake of synaptic vesicles in the full contact fusion model.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] However, other studies have been compiling evidence suggesting that this type of fusion and endocytosis is not always the case.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Two leading mechanisms of action are thought to be responsible for synaptic vesicle recycling: full collapse fusion and the "kiss-and-run" method.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Both mechanisms begin with the formation of the synaptic pore that releases transmitter to the extracellular space.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] After release of the neurotransmitter, the pore can either dilate fully so that the vesicle collapses completely into the synaptic membrane, or it can close rapidly and pinch off the membrane to generate kiss-and-run fusion.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] It has been shown that periods of intense stimulation at neural synapses deplete vesicle count as well as increase cellular capacitance and surface area.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This indicates that after synaptic vesicles release their neurotransmitter payload, they merge with and become part of, the cellular membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] After tagging synaptic vesicles with HRP (horseradish peroxidase), Heuser and Reese found that portions of the cellular membrane at the frog neuromuscular junction were taken up by the cell and converted back into synaptic vesicles.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Studies suggest that the entire cycle of exocytosis, retrieval, and reformation of the synaptic vesicles requires less than 1 minute.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] In full collapse fusion, the synaptic vesicle merges and becomes incorporated into the cell membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The formation of the new membrane is a protein mediated process and can only occur under certain conditions.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] After an action potential, Ca2+ floods to the presynaptic membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Ca2+ binds to specific proteins in the cytoplasm, one of which is synaptotagmin, which in turn trigger the complete fusion of the synaptic vesicle with the cellular membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This complete fusion of the pore is assisted by SNARE proteins.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This large family of proteins mediate docking of synaptic vesicles in an ATP-dependent manner.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] With the help of synaptobrevin on the synaptic vesicle, the t-SNARE complex on the membrane, made up of syntaxin and SNAP-25, can dock, prime, and fuse the synaptic vesicle into the membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The mechanism behind full collapse fusion has been shown to be the target of the botulinum and tetanus toxins.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The botulinum toxin has protease activity which degrades the SNAP-25 protein.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The SNAP-25 protein is required for vesicle fusion that releases neurotransmitters, in particular acetylcholine.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Botulinum toxin essentially cleaves these SNARE proteins, and in doing so, prevents synaptic vesicles from fusing with the cellular synaptic membrane and releasing their neurotransmitters.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Tetanus toxin follows a similar pathway, but instead attacks the protein synaptobrevin on the synaptic vesicle.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] In turn, these neurotoxins prevent synaptic vesicles from completing full collapse fusion.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Without this mechanism in effect, muscle spasms, paralysis, and death can occur.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The second mechanism by which synaptic vesicles are recycled is known as kiss-and-run fusion.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] In this case, the synaptic vesicle "kisses" the cellular membrane, opening a small pore for its neurotransmitter payload to be released through, then closes the pore and is recycled back into the cell.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The kiss-and-run mechanism has been a hotly debated topic.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Its effects have been observed and recorded; however the reason behind its use as opposed to full collapse fusion is still being explored.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] It has been speculated that kiss-and-run is often employed to conserve scarce vesicular resources as well as being utilized to respond to high-frequency inputs.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Experiments have shown that kiss-and-run events do occur.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] First observed by Katz and del Castillo, it was later observed that the kiss-and-run mechanism was different from full collapse fusion in that cellular capacitance did not increase in kiss-and-run events.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This reinforces the idea of a kiss-and-run fashion, the synaptic vesicle releases its payload and then separates from the membrane.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Cells thus appear to have at least two mechanisms to follow for membrane recycling.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Under certain conditions, cells can switch from one mechanism to the other.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Slow, conventional, full collapse fusion predominates the synaptic membrane when Ca2+ levels are low, and the fast kiss-and-run mechanism is followed when Ca2+ levels are high.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Ales *et al.* showed that raised concentrations of extracellular calcium ions shift the preferred mode of recycling and synaptic vesicle release to the kiss-and-run mechanism in a calcium-concentration-dependent manner.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] It has been proposed that during secretion of neurotransmitters at synapses, the mode of exocytosis is modulated by calcium to attain optimal conditions for coupled exocytosis and endocytosis according to synaptic activity.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Experimental evidence suggests that kiss-and-run is the dominant mode of synaptic release at the beginning of stimulus trains.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] In this context, kiss-and-run reflects a high vesicle release probability.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The incidence of kiss-and-run is also increased by rapid firing and stimulation of the neuron, suggesting that the kinetics of this type of release is faster than other forms of vesicle release.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] With the advent of the electron microscope in the early 1950s, nerve endings were found to contain a large number of electron-lucent (transparent to electrons) vesicles.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The term synaptic vesicle was first introduced by De Robertis and Bennett in 1954.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] This was shortly after transmitter release at the frog neuromuscular junction was found to induce postsynaptic miniature end-plate potentials that were ascribed to the release of discrete packages of neurotransmitter (quanta) from the presynaptic nerve terminal.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] It was thus reasonable to hypothesize that the transmitter substance (acetylcholine) was contained in such vesicles, which by a secretory mechanism would release their contents into the synaptic cleft (vesicle hypothesis).
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The missing link was the demonstration that the neurotransmitter acetylcholine is actually contained in synaptic vesicles.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] About ten years later, the application of subcellular fractionation techniques to brain tissue permitted the isolation first of nerve endings (synaptosomes), and subsequently of synaptic vesicles from mammalian brain.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Two competing laboratories were involved in this work, that of Victor P.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Whittaker at the Institute of Animal Physiology, Agricultural Research Council, Babraham, Cambridge, UK and that of Eduardo de Robertis at the Instituto de Anatomía General y Embriología, Facultad de Medicina, Universidad de Buenos Aires, Argentina.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Both groups released synaptic vesicles from isolated synaptosomes by osmotic shock.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The content of acetylcholine in a vesicle was originally estimated to be 1000–2000 molecules.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Subsequent work identified the vesicular localization of other neurotransmitters, such as amino acids, catecholamines, serotonin, and ATP.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] Later, synaptic vesicles could also be isolated from other tissues such as the superior cervical ganglion, or the octopus brain.
[src:synaptic-transmission/synaptic-vesicle] The isolation of highly purified fractions of cholinergic synaptic vesicles from the ray *Torpedo* electric organ was an important step forward in the study of vesicle biochemistry and function.
